        -:   75:
        -:   76:/** \returns a pseudo expression of \c *this with an operator= assuming
        -:   77:  * no aliasing between \c *this and the source expression.
        -:   78:  *
        -:   79:  * More precisely, noalias() allows to bypass the EvalBeforeAssignBit flag.
        -:   80:  * Currently, even though several expressions may alias, only product
        -:   81:  * expressions have this flag. Therefore, noalias() is only useful when
        -:   82:  * the source expression contains a matrix product.
        -:   83:  *
        -:   84:  * Here are some examples where noalias is useful:
        -:   85:  * \code
        -:   86:  * D.noalias()  = A * B;
        -:   87:  * D.noalias() += A.transpose() * B;
        -:   88:  * D.noalias() -= 2 * A * B.adjoint();
        -:   89:  * \endcode
        -:   90:  *
        -:   91:  * On the other hand the following example will lead to a \b wrong result:
        -:   92:  * \code
        -:   93:  * A.noalias() = A * B;
        -:   94:  * \endcode
        -:   95:  * because the result matrix A is also an operand of the matrix product. Therefore,
        -:   96:  * there is no alternative than evaluating A * B in a temporary, that is the default
        -:   97:  * behavior when you write:
        -:   98:  * \code
        -:   99:  * A = A * B;
        -:  100:  * \endcode
        -:  101:  *
        -:  102:  * \sa class NoAlias
        -:  103:  */
        -:  104:template<typename Derived>
     1556:  105:NoAlias<Derived,MatrixBase> EIGEN_DEVICE_FUNC MatrixBase<Derived>::noalias()
        -:  106:{
     1556:  107:  return NoAlias<Derived, Eigen::MatrixBase >(derived());
        -:  108:}
        -:  109:
        -:  110:} // end namespace Eigen
